SIMPLE: myrrh
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Myrrh
<hw>Myrrh</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mirre</ets>,
OF. <ets>mirre</ets>, F. <ets>myrrhe</ets>, L. <ets>myrrha</ets>,
<ets>murra</ets>, Gr. <?/; cf. Ar. <ets>murr</ets> bitter, also myrrh,
Heb. <ets>mar</ets> bitter.]</ety> <def>A gum resin, usually of a
yellowish brown or amber color, of an aromatic odor, and a bitter,
slightly pungent taste. It is valued for its odor and for its medicinal
properties. It exudes from the bark of a shrub of Abyssinia and Arabia,
the <spn>Commiphora Myrrha</spn> (syn. <spn>Balsamodendron Myrrha</spn>)
of the family <fam>Burseraceae</fam>, or from the <spn>Commiphora
abyssinica</spn>. The myrrh of the Bible is supposed to have been partly
the gum above named, and partly the exudation of species of
<gen>Cistus</gen>, or rockrose.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>False myrrh</b></col>. <cd>See the Note under
<er>Bdellium</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrrhic</ent>⟦br⟧
